model_comments: refers to previous version of magna carta; we have inspected the great charter of henry late king of england concerning the liberties of england in these words; references in pr to statutum de tallagio non concedendo and magna carta; as refers to br; whereas in the first year of the reign of your majesty and of our late most gracious sovereign lady queen mary of blessed memory an act of parliament was made intituled an act for declaring the rights and liberties of the subject and for settling the succession of the crown; us refers to br and as
prevcond_comments: refers to previous charters of rights; fw refers to existing differences between english and welsh customs and division this has caused; some rude and ignorant people have made distinction and diversity between the kings subjects of this realm and his subjects of wales whereby great discord variance debate division murmur and sedition hath grown between his said subjects; refers to ways king has been abusing power; people assembled in diverse places and required to lend certain sums of money to the king; charged molested and imprisoned for refusal; soldiers and mariners being dispersed into diverse counties and inhabitants compelled to receive them into their houses; use of martial law against the magna carta to execute subjects; some grievous offenders escaping punishment by laws of realm due to use of martial law and pretense such offenses were punishable only by martial law; whereas the late king james the second by the assistance of divers evil counsellors judges and ministers employed by him did endeavour to subvert and extirpate the protestant religion and the laws and liberties of this kingdom; included assuming power of suspending and making laws; disarming protestants; prosecuting petitioners; keeping a standing army in peacetime; requiring excessive bail; violating freedom of elections to parliament; levying money for the crown by pretence and without parliamentary permission; imposing cruel and unusual punishments
oath_comments: specifies new oaths of allegiance to be taken but not who takes them; oaths hereafter mentioned be taken by all persons of whom the oaths have allegiance and supremacy might be required by law instead of them; corononation oath requires monarch to declare adherence to protestant faith and uphold enactments which secure the protestant succession to the throne; every king and queen of this realm who shall come to and succeed in the imperiall crown of this kingdom by vertue of this act shall have the coronation oath administred to him her or them at their respective coronations according to the act of parliament made in the first year of the reign of his majesty and the said late queen mary intituled an act for establishing the coronation oath; every one of the lords of parliament of great britain and every member of the house of commons of the parliament of great britain shall take the respective oaths appointed to be taken in stead of the oaths of allegiance and supremacy by the act for the abrogating of the oaths of supremacy and allegiance; and make subscribe and audibly repeat the declaration mentioned in the act for the more effectual preserving the kings person and government by disabling papists from sitting in either house of parliament and shall take and subscribe the oath mentioned in the act to declare the alterations in the oath appointed to be taken by the act for the further security of his majestys person and the succession of the crown in the protestant line; at such time and in such manner as the members of both houses of parliament of england are by the said respective acts directed to take make and subscribe the same; it is declared and agreed that these words this realm the crown of this realm and the queen of this realm mentioned in the oaths and declaration contained in the aforesaid acts which were intended to signify the crown and realm of england shall be understood of the crown and realm of great britain; and that in that sense the said oaths and declaration be taken and subscribed by t
fortrad_comments: all the subjects of the united kingdom of great britain shall have full freedom and intercourse of trade and navigation to and from any port or place within the said united kingdom and the dominions and plantations thereunto belonging; all parts of the united kingdom shall have the same allowances encouragements and drawbacks and be under the same prohibitions restrictions and regulations of trade and liable to the same customs and duties on import and export; laws concerning the regulation of trade customs and such excises to which scotland is by virtue of this treaty to be liable be the same in scotland as in england; his majesty's subjects of great britain and ireland shall be entitled to the same privileges and be on the same footing as to encouragements and bounties on the like articles being the growth produce or manufacture of either country respectively and generally in respect of trade and navigation in all ports and places in the united kingdom and its dependencies; all prohibitions and bounties on the export of articles the growth produce or manufacture of either country to the other shall cease
figures_comments: king henry; king edward; king henry ii; henry earl of worcester; sir walter devereux; lord ferrers of chartley; john arnold; john breakenhead; john leonard; william webbe; sir john blunt; george blunt; king edward 1; king edward 3; king james 2; king charles 2; william of orange; mary of orange; princess anne of denmark; princess sophia electress of hanover; king james 1; prince william duke of gloucester; king william 3; queen elizabeth; king william the fourth; queen anne
hosrest_comments: all and every person and persons that is are or shall be reconciled to or shall hold communion with the see or church of rome or shall profess the popish religion or shall marry a papist shall be excluded and be for ever incapable to inherit possess or enjoy the crown and government of this realm; monarch must take oath at coronation declaring that he or she is a faithful protestant; every king and queen of this realm who at any time hereafter shall come to and succeed in the imperial crown of this kingdom shall on the first day of the meeting of the first parliament next after his or her coming to the crown sitting in his or her throne in the house of peers in the presence of the lords and commons therein assembled or at his or her coronation before such person or persons who shall administer the coronation oath to him or her at the time of his or her taking the said oath make subscribe and audibly repeat the accession declaration; provisions for succession of the crown in the protestant line; those who take communion with the catholic church incapable of inheriting as set out in br; whosoever shall hereafter come to the possession of this crown shall joyn in communion with the church of england as by law established; no person who shall hereafter come to the possession of this crown shall go out of the dominions of england scotland or ireland without consent of parliament; succession of the monarchy to the united kingdom of great britain and of the dominions thereto belonging after her most sacred majesty and in default of issue of her majesty be remain and continue to the most excellent princess sophia electoress and dutchess dowager of hanover and the heirs of her body being protestants; all papists and persons marrying papists shall be excluded from and forever incapable to inherit possess or enjoy the imperial crown of great britain; every king or queen succeeding and coming to the royal government of the kingdom of great britain at his or her coronation shall in the presence of all persons present take

em_comments: martial law commissions created before pr and used to execute some subjects; some of your majestys subjects have been by some of the said commissioners put to death when and where if by the laws and statues of the land they had deserved death by the same laws and statutes also they might and by no other ought to have been judged and executed; call for the aforesaid commissions for proceeding by martial law to be revoked and annulled and hereafter no commissions of any like nature issued forth to any person or persons whatsoever to be executed as aforesaid

legrep_comments: in case of the death or legal incapacity of any of the said 16 peers that the aforesaid peers of scotland shall nominate another of their own number in place of the said peer or peers in manner before and after mentioned; if the seat of any of the commoners representing ireland shall become vacant by death or otherwise the counties cities or boroughs shall proceed to a new election; whenever there shall be a vacancy among the lords spiritual by the avoidance of any one of any one of the sees of canterbury york london durham or winchester or of any other see which shall be filled by the translation thereto from any other see of a bishop at that time actually sitting as a lord of parliament such vacancy shall be supplied by the issue of a writ of summons to the bishop who shall be elected to the same see; but if such vacancy be caused by avoidance of any other see in  england or wales who first did homage for his see or for any other see in england or wales of those who have not previously become entitled to such writ; on any lord of appeal in ordinary vacating his office by death resignation or otherwise her majesty may fill up the vacancy by the appointment of another qualified person

votelim_comments: none shall be capable to elect or be elected for any of the said estates but such as are 21 years of age compleat; those occupying a property because of their employment are entitled to vote provided their employer does not live on the premises; owners of rentcharge of rectory or vicarage or chapelry or benefice must own the whole of the rentcharge in order to vote; must be of full age and not subject to any legal incapacity; must reside in premises in the constituency or occupy business premises in the constituency on the last day of the qualifying period; business premises must have yearly value of not less than ten pounds; must have received degree in order to vote in university constituency; women must be 30 years old and occupy premises of yearly value of not less than five pounds or be wife of husband entitled to vote; qualifying period is six months ending on either fifteenth of january or fifteenth of july; qualifiying period is one month for military or naval voters; not more than two joint occupiers can register to vote unless engaged as bona fide partners; man not qualified to vote if commenced to reside in constituency within thirty days before the end of the qualifying period and ceased to reside within thirdy days after the time when he so commenced to reside; conscientious objectors disqualified from voting unless obtain certificate from central military tribunal; must be a british subject or citizen of republic of ireland; must either be resident in constituency on qualifying date or possess non-resident qualification; must be registered in register of parliamentary electors; voters in northern ireland must have been resident there for three months ending on qualifying date; people living in mental institutions not considered resident there; to have non-resident qualification must be occupying as owner or tenant property of yearly value of not less than 10 pounds; must be 18 years of age; prisoners cannot vote
electsch_comments: at a general election all polls shall be held on one day and the day fixed for receiving nominations shall be the same in all constituencies; in the case of a bye-election the poll shall take place on such day as the returning officer may appoint not being less than four or more than eight clear days after the day fixed for nomination; for university elections other than in scotland the poll shall remain open for five days and shall take place on such days as may be fixed by the returning officer commencing not more than twelve and not less than three clear days after the day of nomination
marriage_comments: those who marry papists may not inherit the throne

oath_comments: Senators; Representatives; Members of State Legislatures; all executive and judicial Officers, both of the United States and of the several States
fortrad_comments: 1.8 congress has power to impose duties; imposts; excises; a18 a21 ban and repeal of ban of importation of alcohol
capital_comments: district is mentioned but location to be determined by congress and state cession of territory
hossucc_comments: vice-president; congress can by law designate line of succession in event both president and vice-president are unable to sit
lhrest_comments: must have been a citizen for 7 years; must be an inhabitant of the state they elected in; cannot have taken part in a rebellion or insurrection
uhrest_comments: 9 years a citizen and an inhabitant of the state elected from; cannot have taken part in a rebellion or insurrection
legrep_comments: writs of election; state legislatures can empower executive to issue termporary appointments in senate
votelim_comments: a14.2 may be restricted for participation in rebellion or other crime; states that deny voting rights to males 21 years and over may partially lose representation in legislature; a15 right to vote shall not be denied or abridged on account of race, color, or previous condition of servitude; a19 right to vote shall not be denied or abridged on account of sex; a24 right to vote in primary or other election shall not be denied or abridged by reason of failure to pay poll tax or other tax; a26 right to vote of those 18 and older shall not be denied or abridged
census_comments: census specified; within three years of congress' first meeting and every ten years thereafter; congress legislates method
